AGI -&nbsp; Not to all foreign leaders is reserved the welcome that today the Emperor Naruhito and Empress Masako> have especially granted the President of the Republic, Sergio Mattarella, head of a friend state of Japan with which - as Mattarella reiterated yesterday - Italy has extensive diplomatic and cultural relations. >This morning, at the <a href="https://www.agi.it/politica/news/2025-03-02/vista-sta-sergio-mattarella-in-giappone-30250261/"> second day of institutional visit in the Country of the Levant </a>, Mattarella, accompanied by Mrs Laura, has crossed the threshold of the private residence of the 'Sovranob Celeste'
This residence is located within a vast complex, in the central Chiyoda district of Tokyo, surrounded by the famous Japanese gardens, and completely rebuilt in the post-war period. Here stood the Edo Castle, which for over 250 years has hosted the powerful shoguns, thus representing the political hub of Japan.
<br> Little remains of that historical sacredness: the same residence - explain the workers - is used eminently for private and representative functions. But the Emperor, who does not appear more than twice a year to the public overlooking his home, certainly reserves only at very few great occasions the honors received from the chief of the Quirinale.
After the formal greetings of the imperial couple, marked by the rules of the ceremonial, Mattarella has in fact intertwined with the Emperor Naruhito for references that, in the light of the particular role of the Japanese monarch, which is symbol of the state and unity of the people, are a sign of great attention and respect towards the Italian delegation. Breakfast, subsequently organized in the residence, is considered a courtesy that goes well beyond the act due.&nbsp;
President Mattarella, accompanied by Empress Masako, was the first to sit at a finely arranged table decorated with floral arrangements. At the table, together with high court dignitaries, also the Deputy Minister of Foreign Affairs Edmondo Cirielli, representing the government, the Italian ambassador in Japan, Gianluigi Benedetti, and the Japanese ambassador in Italy, Suzuki Satoshi. At the table, to participate in the breakfast by returning the courtesy received from the Quirinale during their trip to Rome in 2016, also the brother of the Emperor and Crown Prince, Akishino, with the consort. On that occasion, in fact, the princes visited the Palazzo del Quirinale and had the opportunity to entertain President Mattarella before meeting former Premier Matteo Renzi.
&nbsp;
<div </div
<br> Normally the main residence of the imperial family is not open to the public > and rarely welcomes visitors. Only in two occasions a year the Japanese can approach and see the family: on the occasion of the celebrations for the new year, on January 2, when the gardens are open to the public, and on February 23, on the birthday of the Emperor, when the imperial family makes three apparitions and you can sign the wish register.&nbsp;
<h2> Japan's "blue wave"
Since 2009 an Italian Head of State has not crossed the threshold of the Imperial Palace of Tokyo. This honor, granted last time to Giorgio Napolitano, was touched this morning to the President of the Republic Sergio Mattarella, awaited by the Emperor Naruhito and the consort, Empress Masako. Sixteen years have passed and, although Japan is a global industrial power launched in the high tech and I.A. world, the strict court ceremonial - learns - has not undergone significant changes.
The heavenly ruler, a literal translation of his title, is in fact more than one head of state: for many Japanese remains a supernatural and inaccessible figure, despite the public admission of non-direct divine lineage that Emperor Hirohito had to subscribe in 1946, after the defeat in the Second World War (other than using terminologies and linguistic forms still subject to conflicting interpretations).
The Emperor does not know superior authority >e, because of belonging to a dynasty that has its roots in the myth (the birth of Japan thanks to the divine power >), embodies the measure of time and history of the country. Progress has certainly contributed to the myth of this figure, but not the symbol that embodies: the Emperor is a Shinto priest, > guardian of the unity of the people and of the country, although not formally the leader. In particular, Naruhito, very respected and loved by his people, has been in charge since May 2019 and is the 126th emperor of Japan. With the consort, Empress Masako, has definitely helped to renew the imperial image: a degree in history with specialties obtained in Oxford, loves to do sports, travel and knows Europe very well.
The emperor, notoriously, does not express political ideas, but only the values of the Constitution: no interference in public affairs but is a respected element of union, besides being a advocate of peace in the world, harmony and collaboration among peoples. For his people the imperial couple, considered the ambassador of Japan in the world, remains a trait of union between the past and the present of the country. Also for this reason he had toured the world the news, in April of last year, of the "barco" of the imperial family on Instagram. Those who expected a 'conversion' &nbsp; to the glamour of the oldest monarchy > of the world was however disappointed: the Agency of the Imperial House of Japan on social networks has in fact maintained the sobriety and composure that has always characterized it. On the net, there are only photos 'posate'&nbsp; and composed of the family on official occasions. Nothing, in short, that can lend the side to gossip or new ties to appear of the family, always reserved.&nbsp;
&nbsp;

